Food owes to European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, deflation was higher than expected in November – after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British, and Canadian notes, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the lead interest rates. In its opinion, the interest rate cuts would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below 2 percent, or at least close to the 2 percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the middle of the mill: inflation needs to be “debate” to exclude the need for action at a later date.
In November, the inflation rate reached a record high of 12 years in Germany with 3.3 per cent; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Food and energy prices are responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant deterioration in 2007 in the case of food oils and dairy products.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost <0x24>100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts assume a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
