Many places are saved on disinfectants
More than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to inadequate treatment with antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overloading of staff - all factors that are not exactly acceptable to mitigate the infections, according to the lead doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation could not be performed because of the bacterium still in the patient’s body.
By December 10, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant agents were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the lead doctor of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Börocz.
So many infections, caused by multi-resistant agents, have been safely registered in hospitals, but the dark numbers are likely to be higher.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carries about a third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as neck inflammation, almond inflammation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well healing.
However, if the agents are overdosed or improperly applied, antibiotic-resistant bacteria are produced, which are rapidly spreading in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital’s daily routine.
You should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA is just not there where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks during care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment," - said Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, the patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be prevented.
Uncommon sampling
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for inhibiting the formation or spread of the multi-resistant agent, says Karolina Börocz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients delivered and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not so often practiced in Hungarian hospitals.
Last but not least, because there are no grants for this examination from the State Health Fund.
Therefore, most cases only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the agent can be formed, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even less common, says Karolina Börocz.
Saved with disinfectants
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is most commonly transferred from one patient to the other by nursing staff.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are almost lined up, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, even in the less well-established hospitals, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that actually favor the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Börocz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections in the grip causes the health insurance huge costs, so they are combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment in the government program was retained.
After first signs, the program is successful - as evidenced by published data, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared prevention of the development of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
