Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates from the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is essential for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit, which has achieved several records due to its duration, the distance from habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools built by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Wednesday, when the astronauts had unloaded the module Harmony from the Discovery Space Shuttle, a large cylinder-shaped part that is expected to soon include the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module lab.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was, therefore, to implement a 17.5-ton module for power generation via solar collectors already on the ISS, in order to bring it into its final position.
After moving it, the crew began to restructure the solar collectors of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can fold up like chords, was damaged by a clamped cable of about one meter in length.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to further damage the collector.
Astronauts, who initially left the Discovery space shuttle for a check-up, and then had to repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around at the end of the 30-meter remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle, which had been attached to the station, to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resilient, very skilled, it has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After carefully examining the damage, he broke through the faulty cable and fastened a kind of rail on the damaged site.
He was supported by a second spacewalker who remained close to the lock, and, from within, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, Commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey batter, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar collectors that generate several hundred volts, had been designed and built by the astronauts on board the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully folded before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half day of relaxation before today seven astronauts returned to the Discovery space shuttle to be expected to take the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
