After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of the 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, have not been accessed until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and namely, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven states in charge of their administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to conduct investigations, especially about the deportations of prisoners, the prisoners of concentration camps and the health of forced workers, says Reto Meistern, head of these archives, who are being investigated by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CIC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoners’ lists of concentration camps or the detention orders issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, in order to make them the way to their detention.
Today in Bad Arolsen more than 300 permanently handled tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
Nothing fundamentally new can be expected in these documents, said Professor Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
