The Congress approves the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on November 1.
Parallel to the parliamentary drafting, which today ended its meeting with the Senate decision on the amendments to the project, the government published the provisions arising out of the new law with the intention to allow the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of Congress and Senate MPs, who had pursued the goal in their negotiations and votes, to establish the best possible regulation that ensures the safety of investors and ensures that the individual entrepreneurs’ activities are regulated in a way that unifies all trademarks.
The MIFID, which re-establishes the Securities Services Regulations, aims at improving investor protection in addition to modernising the financial markets, increasing the control of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new directive enables both specialized companies and natural or legal persons to provide financial advice, and also contributes to the creation of new financial services firms (ESIS), advisory firms that work together with the investment and mediation companies of securities companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, adding the multilateral systems of securities transactions and the systems for the internationalisation of trade contracts to the regulated circular markets, which would eventually compete with the current economic operators.
The law obliges investment firms to record the focuses of their company profile, the confrontation and the forms of dealing with risks in the market and all projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV’s control task.
The Economic Commission of the Congress subsequently provided further changes, with the decision that the securities securities must now be considered as a complex financial means for the investor due to its high risk rate has been confirmed by the U.S. mortgage and banking crisis (USHpo).
In addition, the entry into force of the Directive on the legal restriction of the working areas of graduates in economics was used; 30 years after the adoption of the Regulation, which limited the working areas reserved for economics scientists, in 1977.
The Senate, for its part, identified new positions in the financial sector, such as those of the economic mediator working on foreign accounts, which does not require authorization by the CNMV and can offer its services to commercialise products and to acquire customers at the same time.
