New Concerns About Natural Gas Conflict Between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is escalating between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian fuel exports to Western Europe being affected.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine, and every dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to EU countries.
The latest conflict between Kiev and Moscow is at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be more calculated, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a drop in exports to Western Europe, which led to a drastic increase in prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the supply of the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom supplements its own stockpiles with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
