Black also expressed concern that the Scottish State Health Service did not have any accurate estimates of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The Chief Financial Controller investigated staff recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a field car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video in Old Bailey in October and was charged with the alleged car bombing in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to hiring foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify pre-trial records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The Auditor-General’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the Board should adopt guidelines on the extraction of the criminal record, which assists employers in controls in different countries.
"While we found evidence of these checks in some staff documents, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their research guidelines to a high degree before hiring, but added: “Our report shows areas in which the system can be improved to ensure accurate information about the number of foreign health co-operation services.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations prior to hiring potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that current pre-employment tests of the NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the executives had trouble identifying those employees who are allowed for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation further found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian have been mostly complied with.
These include passports, work permits, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a concern to me to do this work in view of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in the updated guidelines on control investigations in advance of the recruitment of all employees would also be reflected in the country's assessments.
